% To have just one problem per page, simply put a \clearpage after each problem

\begin{homeworkTask}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Explore your file system!
  \item Whats in your home folder?
  \item How many users are there on your system?
  \item Try an absolute path to get to home!
\end{enumerate}
\end{homeworkTask}

\begin{homeworkTask}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Create a new folder at home
  \item Create an empty file in it
  \item List the file
  \item Rename the file
  \item Move the file one level up
  \item Remove the file. Test if it's really gone.
  \item Remove the folder. Test if it's really gone.
  \item Go to root
  \item Try to create a directory in root
\end{enumerate}
\end{homeworkTask}

\begin{homeworkTask}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Create a directory called python\_course.
  \item Move the course files from your Downloads folder to the course folder
  \item Unpack them with 'tar xzvf [files]'
  \item What files are in there?
\end{enumerate}
\end{homeworkTask}

\begin{homeworkTask}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item How big are your course files?
  \item And how long?
  \item Create a new file
  \item How big and long is it?
\end{enumerate}
\end{homeworkTask}

\begin{homeworkTask}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Open a new file in nano
  \item Write something into it
  \item Save it as test1.txt
  \item Do it again for a 2nd file called test2.txt
  \item Cat both into a new file called test3.txt
  \item Open it with less
  \item Remove all 3 files in a single command (use a wildcard!).
\end{enumerate}
\end{homeworkTask}

\begin{homeworkTask}
In the following tasks we will try to analyse the file 'pristionchus\_mutations.txt' in your course files.
It's a list of mutations and their effects in several Pristionchus strains (surprise!).

Each line corresponds to one mutation. 
The columns stand for:

Strain-Chromosome-Contig-Position-ReferenceBase-MutatedBase-CodingState-Effect-Homologs 

\begin{enumerate}
  \item Understand the contents
  \item Try head and tail
  \item Create a new file containing only the Contig information.
\end{enumerate}
\end{homeworkTask}

\begin{homeworkTask}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Are there SNPs in an 'unc'-gene?
  \item How many SNPs does the file contain in total?
  \item How many SNPs are in exons?
  \item How many SNPs are in exons on Contig0?
\end{enumerate}
\end{homeworkTask}

\begin{homeworkTask}
\begin{enumerate}
  \item How many "C" are mutated? 
  \item How many mutations from "A" to "G"?
  \item How many in MA\_46?
  \item Which strain has the most SNPs?
\end{enumerate}
\end{homeworkTask}





